- Referenced these parameters in the sequentialVertexColoring doc.

pr_body:
Closes #1348, #1362. This PR adds two new pgRouting functions: - **pgr_depthFirstSearch:** Returns a depth first search traversal of the graph. The graph can be directed or undirected. - **pgr_sequentialVertexColoring:** Returns the vertex coloring of an undirected graph, using greedy approach. This is a final merge PR containing commits from several different PRs combined. The intermediate PRs made on the [GSoC-pgRouting](https://github.com/pgRouting/GSoC-pgRouting/) repository are as follows: | Description | Pull Requests | | -----------| --------------------- | |pgr_depthFirstSearch |
  • pgRouting/GSoC-pgRouting#34
  • pgRouting/GSoC-pgRouting#38
  • pgRouting/GSoC-pgRouting#39
  • pgRouting/GSoC-pgRouting#43
| |pgr_sequentialVertexColoring |
  • pgRouting/GSoC-pgRouting#46
  • pgRouting/GSoC-pgRouting#50
  • pgRouting/GSoC-pgRouting#54
  • pgRouting/GSoC-pgRouting#59
| |Code Review & Documentation |
  • pgRouting/GSoC-pgRouting#108
  • pgRouting/GSoC-pgRouting#114
  • pgRouting/GSoC-pgRouting#121

pr_title: pgr_depthFirstSearch and code review GSoC-2020 Week 9
pr_body:
Changes proposed in this pull request:
- Added a new DFS Visitor file
- Modified the implementation of `pgr_depthFirstSearch` for both directed and undirected graphs.
- Added extra edge-cases pgTAP tests to test the modified implementation, and modified the old pgTAP tests.
- Added pgTAP tests to test the equivalence of `pgr_depthFirstSearch` to `pgr_breadthFirstSearch` for the same `max_depth`, for some cases.
- Modified the docqueries for the modified implementation.
- Added the statement to catch cancelation from Postgres user
- Fixed minor styling issues and removed comments in the self-documented code.
- Renamed `source` / `start` to `root` everywhere.
- Removed unnecessary comments & modified the docstrings.
- Removed additional examples from the docqueries, added some examples for depthFirstSearch function.
- Fixed the named parameters ordering & documented the unnamed parameters in a proper way.
- Modified the pgTAP tests & the signatures file after ordering the named parameters properly.

pr_title: Fixing ordering issues in v3 GSoC-2020 Week 7
pr_body:
- Added the pgTAP tests for all the functions already implemented in pgRouting.
- It checks that the function returns the same set of rows for any ordering of input rows.
- Fixed those functions which failed the tests by inserting the edges in sorted order. Some functions have issues, so they aren't fixed yet.

```
SELECT start_vid, end_vid, agg_cost::TEXT FROM pgr_floydWarshall(
```
Then as you can see in my experiment:
https://github.com/cvvergara/pgrouting/runs/874733075?check_suite_focus=true#step:7:373

I added it so that any particular test can be regenerated whenever required, hence we can find out a possible source of error by running the same test locally anytime.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 15, 19, 48, 37, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'krashish8', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 455779011, 'comment_body': 'So, I see your solution is within the drivers
All say: "before creating the graph"
So I ask, what if instead of putting the same `sort`  over and over and over everywhere, you put it inside the graph creation function.
Note that because some of the functions do not need the sorting (sorting takes NlogN time)then the graph creation function needs an additional parameter basically a bool that indicates that the info should be sorted
You can work it out as follows:
- Find the code where the graph gets created
- Add the additional parameter as [default argument](https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/language/default_arguments) (should be the last one of the parameters)
- Set the default value to false. that way you cover:
  - you don't need to edit drivers where the sorting is not needed
  - modifying a driver would be a matter to add `,true` 
  - work this one out together with astar_driver.cpp
- once it works make unique commit when adding that general sort

- [x] Added pgTAP test - server no-crash-test for null parameters - `no_crash_test-depthFirstSearch.sql`.
- [x] Added pgTAP test - parameter types check - `depthFirstSearch-types-check.sql`.
- [x] Added pgTAP test - inner query test - `depthFirstSearch-innerQuery.sql`.
- [x] Added pgTAP unit tests for different small graphs: (`depthFirstSearch-edge-cases.sql`)
  - empty graph
  - vertex not present in the graph
  - negative depths
  - one vertex graph
  - two vertices graph
  - three vertices graph
  - four vertices graph
- [x] Refactored the code, to meet the pgRouting guidelines and Google C++ Style Guide.
- [x] Changed named notation from := to => everywhere (A newer syntax starting from PostgreSQL v9.4).
- [x] Added relevant docstrings and comments in all the C, CPP, and HPP files for better display of Developer's documentation using Doxygen.
- [x] The first function `pgr_depthFirstSearch` is complete, with all the tests and documentation.

pr_body:
Closes #1348, #1362. This PR adds two new pgRouting functions: - **pgr_depthFirstSearch:** Returns a depth first search traversal of the graph. The graph can be directed or undirected. - **pgr_sequentialVertexColoring:** Returns the vertex coloring of an undirected graph, using greedy approach. This is a final merge PR containing commits from several different PRs combined. The intermediate PRs made on the [GSoC-pgRouting](https://github.com/pgRouting/GSoC-pgRouting/) repository are as follows: | Description | Pull Requests | | -----------| --------------------- | |pgr_depthFirstSearch |
  • pgRouting/GSoC-pgRouting#34
  • pgRouting/GSoC-pgRouting#38
  • pgRouting/GSoC-pgRouting#39
  • pgRouting/GSoC-pgRouting#43
| |pgr_sequentialVertexColoring |

pr_body:
Closes #1348, #1362. This PR adds two new pgRouting functions: - **pgr_depthFirstSearch:** Returns a depth first search traversal of the graph. The graph can be directed or undirected. - **pgr_sequentialVertexColoring:** Returns the vertex coloring of an undirected graph, using greedy approach. This is a final merge PR containing commits from several different PRs combined. The intermediate PRs made on the [GSoC-pgRouting](https://github.com/pgRouting/GSoC-pgRouting/) repository are as follows: | Description | Pull Requests | | -----------| --------------------- | |pgr_depthFirstSearch |

pr_body:
Closes #1348, #1362. This PR adds two new pgRouting functions: - **pgr_depthFirstSearch:** Returns a depth first search traversal of the graph. The graph can be directed or undirected. - **pgr_sequentialVertexColoring:** Returns the vertex coloring of an undirected graph, using greedy approach. This is a final merge PR containing commits from several different PRs combined. The intermediate PRs made on the [GSoC-pgRouting](https://github.com/pgRouting/GSoC-pgRouting/) repository are as follows: | Description | Pull Requests | | -----------| --------------------- | |pgr_depthFirstSearch |
  • pgRouting/GSoC-pgRouting#34
  • pgRouting/GSoC-pgRouting#38
  • pgRouting/GSoC-pgRouting#39
  • pgRouting/GSoC-pgRouting#43
| |pgr_sequentialVertexColoring |
  • pgRouting/GSoC-pgRouting#46
  • pgRouting/GSoC-pgRouting#50
  • pgRouting/GSoC-pgRouting#54
  • pgRouting/GSoC-pgRouting#59
| |Code Review & Documentation |
  • pgRouting/GSoC-pgRouting#108
  • pgRouting/GSoC-pgRouting#114
  • pgRouting/GSoC-pgRouting#121

pr_title: pgr_depthFirstSearch and code review GSoC-2020 Week 9
pr_body:
Changes proposed in this pull request:
- Added a new DFS Visitor file
- Modified the implementation of `pgr_depthFirstSearch` for both directed and undirected graphs.
- Added extra edge-cases pgTAP tests to test the modified implementation, and modified the old pgTAP tests.
- Added pgTAP tests to test the equivalence of `pgr_depthFirstSearch` to `pgr_breadthFirstSearch` for the same `max_depth`, for some cases.
- Modified the docqueries for the modified implementation.
- Added the statement to catch cancelation from Postgres user
- Fixed minor styling issues and removed comments in the self-documented code.
- Renamed `source` / `start` to `root` everywhere.
- Removed unnecessary comments & modified the docstrings.
- Removed additional examples from the docqueries, added some examples for depthFirstSearch function.
- Fixed the named parameters ordering & documented the unnamed parameters in a proper way.
- Modified the pgTAP tests & the signatures file after ordering the named parameters properly.

pr_title: Fixing ordering issues in v3 GSoC-2020 Week 7
pr_body:
- Added the pgTAP tests for all the functions already implemented in pgRouting.
- It checks that the function returns the same set of rows for any ordering of input rows.
- Fixed those functions which failed the tests by inserting the edges in sorted order. Some functions have issues, so they aren't fixed yet.

I added it so that any particular test can be regenerated whenever required, hence we can find out a possible source of error by running the same test locally anytime.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 15, 19, 48, 37, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'krashish8', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 455779011, 'comment_body': 'So, I see your solution is within the drivers
All say: "before creating the graph"
So I ask, what if instead of putting the same `sort`  over and over and over everywhere, you put it inside the graph creation function.
Note that because some of the functions do not need the sorting (sorting takes NlogN time)then the graph creation function needs an additional parameter basically a bool that indicates that the info should be sorted
You can work it out as follows:
- Find the code where the graph gets created
- Add the additional parameter as [default argument](https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/language/default_arguments) (should be the last one of the parameters)
- Set the default value to false. that way you cover:
  - you don't need to edit drivers where the sorting is not needed
  - modifying a driver would be a matter to add `,true` 
  - work this one out together with astar_driver.cpp
- once it works make unique commit when adding that general sort

- [x] Added pgTAP test - server no-crash-test for null parameters - `no_crash_test-depthFirstSearch.sql`.
- [x] Added pgTAP test - parameter types check - `depthFirstSearch-types-check.sql`.
- [x] Added pgTAP test - inner query test - `depthFirstSearch-innerQuery.sql`.
- [x] Added pgTAP unit tests for different small graphs: (`depthFirstSearch-edge-cases.sql`)
  - empty graph
  - vertex not present in the graph
  - negative depths
  - one vertex graph
  - two vertices graph
  - three vertices graph
  - four vertices graph
- [x] Refactored the code, to meet the pgRouting guidelines and Google C++ Style Guide.
- [x] Changed named notation from := to => everywhere (A newer syntax starting from PostgreSQL v9.4).
- [x] Added relevant docstrings and comments in all the C, CPP, and HPP files for better display of Developer's documentation using Doxygen.
- [x] The first function `pgr_depthFirstSearch` is complete, with all the tests and documentation.

```
git remote -v

upstream	https://github.com/pgRouting/pgrouting (push)

```
git checkout pgr_depthFirstSearch
git fetch upstream
git rebase upstream/master
git push -f
```
